docs.abstract: The federal government has more lawsuits in the pipeline trying to rein in the tech giants, including another antitrust case against Google that goes to trial next month.
docs.snippet: The federal government has more lawsuits in the pipeline trying to rein in the tech giants, including another antitrust case against Google that goes to trial next month.
docs.lead_paragraph: The U.S. government’s landmark antitrust trial against Google’s search business concluded on Monday with a federal judge’s ruling that the company acted illegally to maintain a monopoly. But the parade of major federal cases challenging the power of the tech giants is just getting going.

headline.main: After Google Antitrust Ruling, Here’s Where Other Big Tech Cases Stand
headline.print_headline: Where Other Cases Stand In Big Tech Antitrust Push

byline.original: By Cecilia Kang and David McCabe

docs.abstract: The e-commerce giant reported a profitable second quarter, but warned that the third quarter will be harder to predict.
docs.snippet: The e-commerce giant reported a profitable second quarter, but warned that the third quarter will be harder to predict.
docs.lead_paragraph: Political violence. The Olympics. An unpredictable presidential election. A chaotic summer of news has distracted consumers, making it hard to know how they will spend, Amazon said Thursday.

headline.main: Amazon Cautions That When the News Gets Nutty, People Shop Less
headline.print_headline: Despite Profitable Quarter, Amazon Issues a Warning

docs.abstract: “Maybe this actually is a chance to press the reset button on the internet.”
docs.snippet: “Maybe this actually is a chance to press the reset button on the internet.”
docs.lead_paragraph: This week, a federal judge ruled that Google acted illegally to maintain a monopoly in online search. David McCabe, a New York Times reporter, joins to discuss what happens next. Then, are we in an A.I. bubble? We weigh in on the wild market swings that started the week and consider the argument that A.I. is overhyped. And finally, it’s time for our new segment: We bat around some of the weirdest recent tech drama — including a MrBeast competition that went awry and a founder who dropped a diss track aimed at a rival. All aboard the Hot-Mess Express.

headline.main: Google’s Monopoly Money + Is the A.I. Bubble Popping? + The Hot-Mess Express

byline.original: By Kevin Roose, Casey Newton, Rachel Cohn, Whitney Jones, Shreeya Sinha, Daniel Ramirez, Dan Powell and Marion Lozano

docs.abstract: Google, Microsoft and Amazon have made deals with A.I. start-ups for their technology and top employees, but have shied from owning the firms. Here’s why.
docs.snippet: Google, Microsoft and Amazon have made deals with A.I. start-ups for their technology and top employees, but have shied from owning the firms. Here’s why.
docs.lead_paragraph: In 2022, Noam Shazeer and Daniel De Freitas left their jobs developing artificial intelligence at Google. They said the tech giant moved too slowly. So they created Character.AI, a chatbot start-up, and raised nearly $200 million.

headline.main: The New A.I. Deal: Buy Everything but the Company
headline.print_headline: Tech Giants See A.I. Deals As Way to Duck Regulation

byline.original: By Erin Griffith and Cade Metz

docs.abstract: He pioneered the bookstore-as-superstore, a retail behemoth that dominated the industry before Amazon overtook it with its online reach.
docs.snippet: He pioneered the bookstore-as-superstore, a retail behemoth that dominated the industry before Amazon overtook it with its online reach.
docs.lead_paragraph: Leonard Riggio, the brash, charismatic and literary-minded businessman who, in founding the giant Barnes & Noble retail chain, transformed the business of selling books as thoroughly as the rise of the paperback once did — and who was cast as both a hero and a villain for doing so — died on Tuesday in Manhattan. He was 83.

headline.main: Leonard Riggio, 83, Dies; Founded Barnes & Noble and Upended Publishing
headline.print_headline: Leonard Riggio, 83, Dies; Turned Barnes & Noble Into Behemoth

docs.abstract: Big technology companies show no signs of slowing their spending on artificial intelligence, even though a payoff still looks a long way away.
docs.snippet: Big technology companies show no signs of slowing their spending on artificial intelligence, even though a payoff still looks a long way away.
docs.lead_paragraph: Mark Zuckerberg, Meta’s chief executive, started 2023 by declaring it the “year of efficiency.” Like several of its big tech peers, Meta cut jobs and mothballed expansion plans.

headline.main: Tech Bosses Preach Patience as They Spend and Spend on A.I.
headline.print_headline: Tech Bosses Preach Patience as They Spend and Spend on A.I.

docs.abstract: The contestants in the internet star’s “Beast Games” expected outlandish challenges and signed contracts that acknowledged risks of serious injury and death. Still, few were prepared for the conditions on set.
